00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:42.230
I actually have a background
in Japanese political economy

00:04:42.230 --> 00:04:44.240
and Asian studies.

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:47.030
And I was doing some
work-- you can go, yeah.

00:04:47.030 --> 00:04:48.440
Hand them out.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:49.520
Thank you.

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:56.660
Now, this is the first work
that we're going to smell, OK?

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:00.690
I got into this, and I
really sort of fell into it.

00:05:00.690 --> 00:05:02.150
I met this guy in
the Gare du Nord.

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:08.570
He is an expert of perfume, and
he was absolutely brilliant.

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:10.820
And I wound up writing
a book about him.

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:14.560
He's a scientist, and he was
working on a biophysical theory

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:16.310
of how we smell, because
we don't actually

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:17.420
know how we smell.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.180
We don't understand
how it works.

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:22.820
But at the same time, the
reason he was working on it is--

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:24.487
don't you have-- oh,
you have a blotter.

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:33.195
We don't think about
the art form that it--

00:05:33.195 --> 00:05:34.430
scent as a medium.

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:37.820
Scent is one of the
most important mediums,

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:39.740
artistic mediums, in the world.

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:42.450
And it is unrecognized.

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:47.400
And it's extraordinary, I
would posit to you that scent

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:53.760
is a medium that is right now
in the stage of recognition

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:58.950
by the Academy, gallerists,
museums, the public,

00:05:58.950 --> 00:06:02.130
as photography was in
the 1950s and '60s.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:06.480
Photography was viewed
as being this craft,

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:09.810
this interesting thing
that, basically, you

00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:12.120
had a photograph,
you had some reality,

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:14.550
and it was about as artistic
as looking in the mirror

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:17.970
or seeing somebody else
reflected in a glass.

00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:20.640
It was just not recognized
as artistic at all.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:23.250
And then we came to
understand that, actually,

00:06:23.250 --> 00:06:27.810
every photograph is a lie,
the lie in the best sense.

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:30.622
Cindy Sherman-- there was this
wonderful biography of her,

00:06:30.622 --> 00:06:32.080
and she was asked
why-- because she

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:35.070
used to be a painter, and
then she started photography.

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:37.505
And she was asked, well,
why did you switch?

00:06:37.505 --> 00:06:38.880
And she sort of
thought about it,

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:40.830
and she said, um,
I don't know, I

00:06:40.830 --> 00:06:45.360
guess it was easier to
lie with the camera.

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:49.440
And all art is artificial,
in the best sense.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:51.152
It has to be.

00:06:51.152 --> 00:06:52.750
It has to be.

00:06:52.750 --> 00:06:54.790
Because it has to
have a mind behind it

00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:57.940
that has a point of
view that has a desire

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:01.030
to create a reality
to present something

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:06.000
to you, to force you to
perceive the world in the way

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.190
that it wants you to.

00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:08.910
All right?

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.790
Now, this is one of the
most extraordinary works

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:17.050
of olfactory art in the
past 20 years or even more.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:22.380
This is a neo-romanticist
work by an artist

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:28.230
named Pierre [? Nugrin, ?]
who is brilliant, brilliant.

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:31.445
And it is a--

00:07:31.445 --> 00:07:33.570
it's a relatively recent
work, as a matter of fact.

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:34.530
I should know the--

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:35.947
I'm forgetting the
year right now.

00:07:35.947 --> 00:07:40.740
But it came out, and it
was, I think, something--

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:44.530
I think that this
is the greatest--

00:07:44.530 --> 00:07:47.350
an extraordinary
masterpiece in several ways.

00:07:47.350 --> 00:07:49.920
First of all, as with
everything, paint--

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:54.450
by the way, scent is the
equal of paint and clay

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:57.240
and music and
architecture and film.

00:07:57.240 --> 00:07:59.160
It is absolutely
the equal of those.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:02.670
And it is also understood
in this highly-developed

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:06.210
vocabulary that we have for art.

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:08.840
It fits in my purpose.

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:11.010
I created the Department
of Olfactory Art

00:08:11.010 --> 00:08:14.130
at the Museum of Arts
and Design in New York.

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:18.210
Before that, I was the
New York Times art critic,

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:21.750
and this was the medium that
works created in this, OK?

00:08:21.750 --> 00:08:25.290
So I think that we
really need to understand

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:26.550
this is as a work.

00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:32.610
It fits into the schools of
art as we understand them.

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:35.250
Do you smell how--

00:08:35.250 --> 00:08:37.080
if you know anything
about romanticism,

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:39.360
everything the
Romanticists believed,

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:41.617
both in literature and music
and the other mediums--

00:08:41.617 --> 00:08:43.200
and those are very
different mediums--

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:45.660
but romanticism is
represented in them.

00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:48.630
Not every school is
represented in every medium.

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:54.470
In this case, it was mostly
literature and music.

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:56.700
But this is a work
of romanticism.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:01.560
Romanticists rejected
rationality emphatically.

00:09:01.560 --> 00:09:06.915
They rejected thought as the
source of logic and rationale

00:09:06.915 --> 00:09:12.570
and these other sorts of
things as a way to find truth.

00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:15.540
And this, I find,
is non-structured.

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:17.700
It is not abstract
expressionist,

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:22.575
because it has very, very
specific real-world references.

00:09:22.575 --> 00:09:25.050
Do you smell the certain things?

00:09:25.050 --> 00:09:27.820
There is a-- and I hate--

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:31.140
and we apply such
a poor vocabulary

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:34.680
to this medium, this
artistic medium,

00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:37.620
because it is not
recognized as such yet.

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:41.010
And we reduce it
to "notes" and sort

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:42.360
of stupid things like that.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:44.640
It's a moronic-- well,
what are the notes?

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:47.160
Well, I mean, Jesus,
look at a Rembrandt.

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:48.510
Well, what are the colors?

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:50.250
Oh, here's black,
and here's red.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:51.600
Oh, there's a little yellow.

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:53.010
Who gives a damn?

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:54.390
It's a Rembrandt.

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:57.180
You don't wear the color--
you don't look at the colors,

00:09:57.180 --> 00:09:58.230
you look at the painting.

00:09:58.230 --> 00:09:59.160
You look at the work.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:01.060
You do not wear the notes or--

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:03.810
and this is the correct way
to say it-- raw materials.

00:10:03.810 --> 00:10:05.150
OK?

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:07.950
You wear the work of art,
and you wear it on skin.

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:08.970
And it's made for skin.

00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:10.290
As a matter of fact,
we were talking,

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:12.582
and this is something that's
very interesting, that I'm

00:10:12.582 --> 00:10:15.840
paired with Dominique, because
this is the only other art

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:20.850
medium that is created to be
worn on an extraordinarily

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:24.458
weird canvas, human skin.

00:10:24.458 --> 00:10:25.770
OK?

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:27.650
Now, this is wonderful.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:31.020
Gender-- I read
about this a lot.

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:35.100
Look, gender is very, very
specific in this medium.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:37.530
Said art was never gendered.

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:39.840
It is ridiculous.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:42.720
Perfumers-- olfactory artists--

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:43.770
hate it.

00:10:43.770 --> 00:10:44.580
They hate it.

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:46.530
They're not allowed to
talk about it overtly,

00:10:46.530 --> 00:10:51.060
because they basically
work for corporations

00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:52.380
who want to sell this--

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:59.770
scent is a medium that
is hugely colonized by--

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:01.770
damn it, how much
time do I have?

00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:03.180
- You have-- I can tell you.

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:05.030
You're left with
five and a half.

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:05.780
- Five and a half.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:06.330
OK, thank you.

00:11:06.330 --> 00:11:07.020
Well, keep me honest.

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:08.687
So I'm just going to
say this, and we're

00:11:08.687 --> 00:11:11.460
going to do the next one.

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:14.610
They hate it-- you know, as
one of the greatest olfactory

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:19.220
artists, Jean-Claude
Ellena, said to me--

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:21.380
in private, but
now I'll out him--

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:23.960
he said, what about music?

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:28.040
He said, is Bartok for men
and Beethoven for women?

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:31.340
Is Radiohead for women
and the Beatles for men?

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:33.882
I mean, it would-- it's
ridiculous on its face.

00:11:33.882 --> 00:11:35.090
So why do we do it with this?

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:38.090
For one very, very
specific reason--

00:11:38.090 --> 00:11:41.930
post-war, one of the things
that American companies wanted

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:42.950
to do--

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:45.350
perfume is one of the greatest
ways-- along with film,

00:11:45.350 --> 00:11:45.560
by the way.

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:47.518
Film is another medium
that's usually colonized

00:11:47.518 --> 00:11:49.640
by corporate interests.

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:53.600
Warner Brothers, Paramount,
Fox, 20th Century Fox, so what?

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:54.230
Disney.

00:11:54.230 --> 00:11:55.280
And that's fine.

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:58.130
That's fine, and there are great
works of art that are actually

00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:00.590
made by these companies.

00:12:00.590 --> 00:12:03.050
Toy Story made a billion,
two billion dollars,

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:04.160
whatever it is.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:05.883
It's the most commercial
film, in a way,

00:12:05.883 --> 00:12:06.800
that you've ever seen.

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:08.280
It is a work of art.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:11.180
It's extraordinary
at the same time, OK?

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:13.500
This was made to make money.

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:16.400
All art is created
to make money, OK?

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:18.650
Let's be clear about that.

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:20.480
But this, this is gorgeous.

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:23.930
After the war, you
wanted to make money.

00:12:23.930 --> 00:12:27.680
It's an incredibly commercial--
lucrative, sorry, lucrative

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:28.640
medium.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:30.440
The only reason that you had--

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:33.170
suddenly perfume was
gendered is that they wanted

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:37.160
to sell perfume to a culture,
to men in a culture that

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:40.970
had no cultural history of
scent as an art, which is,

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:43.320
of course, American culture.

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:46.160
And so what they did
was they divided it

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:48.990
into masculines and feminines.

00:12:48.990 --> 00:12:50.690
And they were
basically-- if it said

00:12:50.690 --> 00:12:55.550
"for him," that is only
giving heterosexual men

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:58.700
psycho-emotional
permission to wear scent.

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:00.200
It's the only reason it exists.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:01.680
Next one?

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:03.530
OK, so this is--

00:13:03.530 --> 00:13:05.500
notice I don't want
to get into the--

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:07.490
I'm going to tell you
later, but I don't

00:13:07.490 --> 00:13:08.850
want to get into it right now.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:09.950
I don't want to talk
about the brand.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.158
I don't want to talk about
the creative director, who

00:13:12.158 --> 00:13:14.480
in this case is actually
very, very important, OK?

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:15.680
Please keep these separate.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:17.270
Remember that you're
smelling the second one.

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:19.370
Put the first one in your
pocket or somewhere else.

00:13:19.370 --> 00:13:20.480
You're welcome to
keep it, but I just

00:13:20.480 --> 00:13:21.688
don't want you to confuse it.

00:13:21.688 --> 00:13:26.660
OK, now this-- do you
sense how different this

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:28.880
is as a work of art?

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:38.160
We have gone from Rachmaninoff
to, if you will, Philip Glass.

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:40.040
- Yes.

00:13:40.040 --> 00:13:43.970
- This is a work of minimalism.

00:13:43.970 --> 00:13:46.560
It presents as a whole.

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:49.330
The other-- the work of
romanticism, it's huge.

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:49.910
You saw.

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:51.710
It was going in every
single direction.

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:52.940
It was speaking loudly.

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:55.580
It was singing.

00:13:55.580 --> 00:13:57.560
There was texture to it.

00:13:57.560 --> 00:13:59.360
It was absolutely extraordinary.

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:00.050
OK?

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:05.300
This is something-- minimalism
as a philosophy really

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:08.180
was not just simplicity.

00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:09.270
Simplicity was part of it.

00:14:09.270 --> 00:14:11.090
But minimalism,
philosophically, really

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:13.250
was an effort-- how
much time do I have?

00:14:13.250 --> 00:14:14.780
- Two and a half.

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:16.160
- OK, we're fine.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:21.710
So, minimalism was a way of
presenting just the material

00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:23.840
and the beauty of the material.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:25.970
And this is a
combination of both.

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:28.173
This is a presentation
of the materials,

00:14:28.173 --> 00:14:29.840
which, again, I'm not
going to get into,

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:30.923
because it doesn't matter.

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:35.530
Maybe it does matter.

00:14:35.530 --> 00:14:37.330
One of the materials
in this case--

00:14:37.330 --> 00:14:39.040
maybe it's legitimate now.

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:42.790
I just hate it so much that I
