00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:44.140
So I'm being extremist.

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:45.640
I'm taking an
extremist position.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.830
If you look at a work of
architecture, Renzo Piano's--

00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:50.903
the New York Times, for
example, where I worked.

00:14:50.903 --> 00:14:53.320
I mean, it's very interesting,
the materials that he used.

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:54.280
And you could talk
about the materials,

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:56.980
but only in the service of
understanding the overall work

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:57.820
of architecture.

00:14:57.820 --> 00:14:59.918
So to understand this,
there's a molecule in here

00:14:59.918 --> 00:15:00.960
that is very interesting.

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:04.000
They're called-- they're
like, three benzyl, four

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:05.920
hexyl, whatever the hell it is.

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:06.850
Sorry about that.

00:15:06.850 --> 00:15:11.020
But you know, they're
called lactones--

00:15:11.020 --> 00:15:13.200
lactic acid milk.

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:15.484
Do you smell that?

00:15:15.484 --> 00:15:18.030
Do you smell the milky quality?

00:15:18.030 --> 00:15:22.520
It's a very, very interesting
presentation of it.

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:24.430
I think that it's also
sort of-- there's sort

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:26.530
of a wood aspect to it.

00:15:26.530 --> 00:15:27.340
One minute.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:30.190
Let's go out with the last one.

00:15:30.190 --> 00:15:35.130
But it is as if you were
