00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:08.960
But it's freaking great.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:10.120
Isn't that amazing?

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:11.020
- It's glorious.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:13.600
- So, this is truly--

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:16.330
this is interesting, because
this is a work of neo,

00:16:16.330 --> 00:16:17.065
if you will--

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:27.940
no, I think it's best understood
as a work of hyperrealism.

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:30.790
It is a realist portraiture.

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:33.360
And I'm actually going to
ask you, what is this in--

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:34.900
this is an olfactory photograph.

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:37.420
What is it a photograph of?

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:39.100
Lilac, exactly.

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:41.170
Yeah.

00:16:41.170 --> 00:16:43.380
The artist is-- oh
my gosh, I forgot.

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.730
The artist of the
Dries van Noten--

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:46.870
who the hell?

00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:51.850
Now I can't remember
the perfumer, who is--

00:16:51.850 --> 00:16:54.188
aw, Frederick let us down.

00:16:54.188 --> 00:16:55.730
He didn't put the
name of the artist.

00:16:55.730 --> 00:16:56.510
Now I can't remember.

00:16:56.510 --> 00:16:58.190
I think-- I'm going
to go out on a limb.

00:16:58.190 --> 00:17:00.748
I think it was Bruno
Jovanovic, I think.

00:17:00.748 --> 00:17:01.790
God help me if I'm wrong.

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:03.170
Bruno is very, very interesting.

00:17:03.170 --> 00:17:04.970
He's a relatively young artist.

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:06.800
But this is just extraordinary.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:12.380
And this artist is one of
the great, great olfactory

00:17:12.380 --> 00:17:15.530
artists of the late 20th,
early 21st centuries.

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:20.300
Her name is Olivia
Giacobetti, and she

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:24.950
has created here a work
of hyperrealism-- realism

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:27.440
because you can tell
that it's lilac.

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:31.040
But the way that it's
presented is in, again,

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.130
a way that a
hyperrealist painter

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:38.340
would present that visually,
or a hyperrealist photograph.

00:17:38.340 --> 00:17:41.270
You think of Mapplethorpe's--
oh, how much time do I have?

00:17:41.270 --> 00:17:41.790
Am I over?

00:17:41.790 --> 00:17:42.290
- Yes.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:42.600
- OK.

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:43.100
I'm over.

00:17:43.100 --> 00:17:45.230
So, last comment--

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:49.910
Mapplethorpe's flowers,
those are not just flowers.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:50.960
You see a flower.

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:53.960
You see so much more,
the symbolism of this.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:56.000
This is extraordinary.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.410
It is not just real.

00:17:57.410 --> 00:17:58.820
It is not just immediate.

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:01.070
It is hyperreal.

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:04.460
It is something that's
over-- it is an experience

00:18:04.460 --> 00:18:08.690
of the object-- the very
specific object in this case,

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:10.820
which the others were not--

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:16.280
that forces you to reconceive
reality, like all art should.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:17.360
- Thank you.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:19.050
Thank you so much.

00:18:19.050 --> 00:18:23.810
Can you make these last all day?

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:27.020
- The length of time that
a work of olfactory art

00:18:27.020 --> 00:18:30.470
lasts, it depends on its
composition, its construction--

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:34.790
and the technical
mastery of the artist.

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:38.080
- Well, thank you again
so much, Chandler.

00:18:38.080 --> 00:18:42.725
And now let me turn it over to
Dominique Holmes and tattoos.

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:56.720
- When modern tattooing
started to emerge

00:18:56.720 --> 00:19:00.800
in the Western culture
in the late 19th century,

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:04.220
it was predominantly men
who were getting tattooed.

00:19:04.220 --> 00:19:06.950
But this was pretty much just
down to the greater autonomy

00:19:06.950 --> 00:19:09.630
they were afforded.

00:19:09.630 --> 00:19:12.020
But the early 20th
century saw women

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:16.340
such as Jesse Knight and Maud
Stevens breaking the mold

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:20.238
and becoming very much respected
collectors and tattooers

00:19:20.238 --> 00:19:21.030
in their own right.

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:29.110
The 1920s signified the
first significant shift

00:19:29.110 --> 00:19:32.260
in the demographic of
the tattooed individual,

00:19:32.260 --> 00:19:35.320
but also, significantly,
the first example of

00:19:35.320 --> 00:19:38.850
tattoos being used as
a political statement.

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:45.140
The rise of the
suffragette movement

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:48.440
saw many society women
seeking out tattoos

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:51.180
as a way to symbolize
their crusade.

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:53.780
And they would wear them
very proudly as a mark

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:57.420
of their rebellion and
their independence.

00:19:57.420 --> 00:20:02.480
And this impact that they
had led to tattoos becoming

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:04.700
much more popular
amongst both men

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:08.030
and women of all
social backgrounds,

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:13.460
especially as tattoos
develop these very

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:15.530
romantic and
patriotic connotations

00:20:15.530 --> 00:20:18.830
throughout the war.

00:20:18.830 --> 00:20:25.100
However, the 1960s saw
a very dramatic shift

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:29.600
in the attitudes
towards tattoos.

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:32.570
The growing association
of tattooing

00:20:32.570 --> 00:20:35.930
with gang culture in
the criminal underworld

00:20:35.930 --> 00:20:38.375
led to an extreme
masculinization

00:20:38.375 --> 00:20:41.600
of the aesthetic.

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:46.550
And around the same time, an
alarming hepatitis outbreak

00:20:46.550 --> 00:20:48.500
combined with this
and really sent

00:20:48.500 --> 00:20:52.910
tattooing underground,
where it became synonymous

00:20:52.910 --> 00:20:55.385
with the misfits of society.

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:03.730
But then, what we see
again, the emergence

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:09.220
of the sexual revolution and
the women's liberation movement

00:21:09.220 --> 00:21:14.350
led to nonconformist women
of all social and political

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:20.440
backgrounds looking
for ways to dismantle

00:21:20.440 --> 00:21:25.210
the preconceived
ideas of femininity.

00:21:25.210 --> 00:21:27.820
And what better
way to do this than

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:30.430
by marking your
body with something

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:34.540
which had come to represent the
height of extreme masculinity?

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:43.330
In 1970, Janis
Joplin very publicly

00:21:43.330 --> 00:21:47.410
declared that the tattoo
she wears on her wrist

00:21:47.410 --> 00:21:51.160
was a mark of
women's liberation.

00:21:53.890 --> 00:21:58.770
Now, her artist, Lyle Tuttle,
who's very, very well-known,

00:21:58.770 --> 00:22:03.040
well-respected
tattooer, he later

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:05.380
went on to describe
how the number of women

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:08.590
he tattooed following
on from Joplin

00:22:08.590 --> 00:22:12.760
increased so dramatically
that he actually credited her

00:22:12.760 --> 00:22:16.480
with the shift in the
acceptance of tattoos

00:22:16.480 --> 00:22:17.810
within mainstream culture.

00:22:21.995 --> 00:22:24.370
I'm going to start to introduce
you to some of my clients

00:22:24.370 --> 00:22:25.230
as we go, as well.

00:22:27.810 --> 00:22:33.660
The anti-feminist backlash
that arose in the '80s

00:22:33.660 --> 00:22:37.880
saw the media start to promote
a very demure, submissive,

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:46.140
and passive appearance
and expression for women.

00:22:46.140 --> 00:22:49.470
And this very
hyperfeminine appearance

00:22:49.470 --> 00:22:53.940
became the
aspirational aesthetic.

00:22:53.940 --> 00:23:01.470
And alongside this, the
rebellious nature of tattooing

00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:06.210
and the connotations that it
had with these revolutionary,

00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:09.990
strong, rebellious
women saw it really

00:23:09.990 --> 00:23:16.200
become the antithesis of
this expected behavior.

00:23:16.200 --> 00:23:18.090
And what we've
seen is this stigma

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:20.280
it was given has been
very hard to shift,

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:21.690
even all these years later.

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:28.710
As we entered the
21st century, the rise

00:23:28.710 --> 00:23:34.260
in the mainstream appreciation,
I suppose, of tattooing

00:23:34.260 --> 00:23:39.000
has seen it become more popular
than it's ever been before.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.590
A study conducted by the Dalia
Research Center in Germany

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:48.240
last year has found
that more than a third

00:23:48.240 --> 00:23:52.780
of adults across the world are
now believed to be tattooed.

00:23:52.780 --> 00:23:56.800
And, interestingly,
for the first time,

00:23:56.800 --> 00:24:00.240
women actually outnumber men.

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:05.880
But the study also found
that women are almost twice

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:12.360
as likely to feel and to
receive judgmental and negative

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:16.090
comments and attitudes about
their tattoos than men.

00:24:21.230 --> 00:24:28.220
These lists are examples of
words used to describe tattoos,

00:24:28.220 --> 00:24:33.050
either for men or for women, on
a very basic internet search.

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:40.570
Now, these extreme contrasts
depict the gendering

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:43.720
of tattoo and tattoo
imagery that we've

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:47.980
seen emerge alongside
its surge in popularity.

00:24:47.980 --> 00:24:53.050
But the words are also
very much synonymous

00:24:53.050 --> 00:24:57.490
with our society's
expectations on the behaviors

00:24:57.490 --> 00:24:59.005
of the two binary genders.

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:07.290
When we think about the
toughness and the strength

00:25:07.290 --> 00:25:11.580
and the rebellion that are
associated with tattooing,

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:13.800
these are also things
that are associated

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:17.610
with aspirational male behavior.

00:25:17.610 --> 00:25:19.980
And so, as we've
seen, tattoos have

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:25.780
been a very welcomed part of
male culture for generations.

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:30.250
But these words and
these ideas very much

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:36.340
oppose expected standards of
behavior projected onto women.

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:42.250
And so what we see is
for women, every tattoo

00:25:42.250 --> 00:25:47.120
acts as a political statement,
whether intentional or not.

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:50.770
And this is why they've
become so embraced as a way

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:54.190
to reject these gendered
expectations projected

00:25:54.190 --> 00:25:54.690
onto them.

00:25:58.950 --> 00:26:02.140
Now I'm going to take you
back to the 1990s for a moment

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:06.635
and back to the growing trend
amongst women for lower back

00:26:06.635 --> 00:26:07.135
tattoos.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:13.010
Now, it's unknown exactly when
the phrase was first coined,

00:26:13.010 --> 00:26:15.680
but this style of
tattooing would go on

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:17.690
to be better-known
as the tramp stamp.

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:26.390
Now, this offensive term and
the many other equally sexist

00:26:26.390 --> 00:26:29.180
and derogatory alternatives
that you can see-- this

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:32.780
is a list from Urban Thesaurus.

00:26:32.780 --> 00:26:34.400
And I've actually
had to cut it down,

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:37.010
because there were so
many, and some of them

00:26:37.010 --> 00:26:43.280
were actually, I felt, too
offensive to put up there.

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:49.010
But this is an example of the
slut shaming and the misogyny

00:26:49.010 --> 00:26:54.230
that is directed towards women
who choose to be tattooed.

00:26:54.230 --> 00:26:59.480
Two separate studies
carried out in 2004 and 2013

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:02.840
both found that tattooed
women are perceived

00:27:02.840 --> 00:27:06.500
to be more sexually promiscuous
than their untattooed

00:27:06.500 --> 00:27:07.400
counterparts.

00:27:12.070 --> 00:27:18.670
This imbalance in the social
perceptions and acceptance

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:22.900
of men and women with tattoos
runs very much parallel

00:27:22.900 --> 00:27:25.420
with the way that our
patriarchal culture

00:27:25.420 --> 00:27:28.780
treats the two binary genders.

00:27:28.780 --> 00:27:31.870
As we've seen,
historically, tattooed women

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:35.320
represent the rebellious
and the revolutionary.

00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:38.500
And for the patriarchy,
there's nothing

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:41.520
that they fear more than
an angry, strong woman.

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:48.820
As women are constantly battling
with the beauty standards that

00:27:48.820 --> 00:27:53.800
are imposed upon them by
the media and by society,

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:58.240
we're starting to see
tattoos as a tool that

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:03.100
can be used to redefine these
conventional ideals and a way

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:08.710
to form our own visions
and definitions of what

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:10.195
it means to be female.

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:16.830
For myself and for many
female-identifying and

00:28:16.830 --> 00:28:20.310
female-presenting individuals
in the queer community,

00:28:20.310 --> 00:28:24.000
tattoos have become an important
part of our appearance, which

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:31.170
we formulate and we utilize
to deconstruct the beauty

00:28:31.170 --> 00:28:34.620
standards that have been
conditioned, really,

00:28:34.620 --> 00:28:37.680
by and for the male gaze.

00:28:37.680 --> 00:28:46.500
And in doing so, we can
form new definitions,

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:51.840
I suppose, away from the
heteronormative ideals

00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:54.660
of femininity.

00:28:54.660 --> 00:28:58.110
But equally, women
are increasingly

00:28:58.110 --> 00:29:02.220
utilizing the political and
the masculine connotations

00:29:02.220 --> 00:29:06.930
associated with
tattoos, but doing so

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:11.820
without necessarily
losing their femininity

00:29:11.820 --> 00:29:14.700
and losing their
female appearance.

00:29:14.700 --> 00:29:19.590
Many of my clients choose
traditionally feminine designs

00:29:19.590 --> 00:29:23.160
and wear them almost
like a kind of jewelry

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:26.550
as a way to enhance
their female form.

00:29:26.550 --> 00:29:31.380
And this is actually reminiscent
of the ancient Egyptians,

00:29:31.380 --> 00:29:34.020
for whom the women
would adorn their skin

00:29:34.020 --> 00:29:37.080
with decorative patterns very
reminiscent of the jewelry

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:38.130
they wore.

00:29:38.130 --> 00:29:40.693
And it was very much
considered a sign of beauty

00:29:40.693 --> 00:29:41.360
and of strength.

00:29:44.150 --> 00:29:46.430
But either way,
what we're seeing

00:29:46.430 --> 00:29:51.680
is, it's actually the rebellious
act of tattooing in itself

00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:58.970
which women are using
to really break down

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:02.900
these outdated
ideas of femininity.

00:30:07.310 --> 00:30:12.230
People often assume that I
tattoo more women than men.

00:30:12.230 --> 00:30:15.830
And it's quite a lazy
assumption based, primarily,

00:30:15.830 --> 00:30:18.380
on the aesthetic
of my work, which

00:30:18.380 --> 00:30:23.510
is considered delicate and
intricate and traditionally

00:30:23.510 --> 00:30:25.340
feminine.

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:30.200
But actually, my client base
covers all gender identities

00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:33.140
fairly evenly.

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:35.480
And so what this
demonstrates in itself

00:30:35.480 --> 00:30:40.190
is that it's also quite
possible to subvert this idea

00:30:40.190 --> 00:30:44.990
that a tattoo must be a
masculine accessory just

00:30:44.990 --> 00:30:48.410
through the choice of
design that is worn.

00:30:51.152 --> 00:30:53.610
I know I'm running out of time,
so I'm going to try and get

00:30:53.610 --> 00:30:56.550
through this quickly.

00:30:56.550 --> 00:31:00.180
My client James finds
that his tattoos

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:05.130
are referred to as
feminine and girly simply

00:31:05.130 --> 00:31:08.820
because of the subject
matter of the tattoos.

00:31:08.820 --> 00:31:13.800
But to him, they're
actually a true reflection

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:18.120
of his own perceived
gender identity, which

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:19.680
is that of a young
man who connects

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:23.880
very much with the feminine
aspects of life just as much

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:27.620
as the masculine.

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:29.380
Now, you've all been given--

00:31:29.380 --> 00:31:34.900
or will be given-- a temporary
tattoo to take away with you.

00:31:34.900 --> 00:31:37.960
So even those of you who
don't have permanent ink

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:40.720
can experience what it's
like to be perceived

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:43.780
as a tattooed individual.

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:48.160
And these designs are based on
actual tattoos that I've done.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:50.890
And I wanted to pick
these in particular

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:53.470
because I feel like as
much as you might want

00:31:53.470 --> 00:31:58.690
to try to categorize them
according to, say, the lists

00:31:58.690 --> 00:32:01.900
that we looked at or according
to ideas of what tattoos

00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:07.420
for men or women
would be, I think

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:11.290
you'd be hard-pressed to assign
a gender to these designs.

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:18.570
I'm just going to finish with
this, one of my favorite--

00:32:18.570 --> 00:32:22.230
one of my favorite pictures,
one of my favorite clients.

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:25.270
And I just want to finish--
sorry, I'm so over--

00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:31.140
by saying that tattoos
represent such an important way

00:32:31.140 --> 00:32:35.130
to portray a greater spectrum
of gender identities,

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:37.950
because we can use imagery
that would not usually

00:32:37.950 --> 00:32:41.790
be associated with
our perceived gender

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:46.620
and wear it in a way that
really projects onto the world

00:32:46.620 --> 00:32:50.280
our identity and how we
want people to see it.

00:32:50.280 --> 00:32:57.750
And the permanence of a
tattoo, the symbolic nature

00:32:57.750 --> 00:33:00.270
of the permanence, is
something which says,

00:33:00.270 --> 00:33:01.290
this is not a phase.

00:33:01.290 --> 00:33:02.400
This is not temporary.

00:33:02.400 --> 00:33:07.740
This is a true
expression of who I am

00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:10.210
and how I want you to see me.

00:33:10.210 --> 00:33:10.710
Thank you.

00:33:21.740 --> 00:33:22.610
- Thank you both.

00:33:22.610 --> 00:33:27.080
It was wonderful and intriguing.

00:33:27.080 --> 00:33:32.510
And the connections with
gender that you finished with,

00:33:32.510 --> 00:33:37.160
Dominique, made me think
about that and the permanence

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:43.370
of tattoos, given the
fact that we think

00:33:43.370 --> 00:33:47.120
about ways to undermine
that permanence

00:33:47.120 --> 00:33:50.840
and that there could
be shifts in our sense

00:33:50.840 --> 00:33:52.470
of our own identity.

00:33:52.470 --> 00:33:55.940
So I wanted to ask you a little
bit how, in your thinking

00:33:55.940 --> 00:34:00.230
and in your practice, you deal
with people who suddenly feel

00:34:00.230 --> 00:34:04.340
that a tattoo they had is
something they want to distance

00:34:04.340 --> 00:34:07.190
themselves from,
the way they might

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:10.219
about any other
form of embodiment

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:14.179
that they felt was
fixed and anchored?

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:16.429
Of course, I know
you can just go

00:34:16.429 --> 00:34:18.350
through the process
of removing them,

00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:23.179
but is that part
of your experience?

00:34:23.179 --> 00:34:28.100
Or are they stable, and people
say, this is me, like my--

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:32.469
- I think there's a way of--

00:34:32.469 --> 00:34:36.070
obviously, certain changes
that we go through in life,

00:34:36.070 --> 00:34:40.300
we might like things less
as we get older, especially

00:34:40.300 --> 00:34:42.219
the aesthetics of a tattoo.

00:34:42.219 --> 00:34:45.370
We might change our mind
about what we like to look at

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:46.960
or, yeah, what
something might mean.

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:49.870
But I think there's
an important lesson

00:34:49.870 --> 00:34:51.760
that you can learn
from a tattoo, which

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:56.560
is to maybe just accept and
let go a bit-- like, let

00:34:56.560 --> 00:34:58.450
go of the negative
association that you

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:01.300
might have with something
you no longer want.

00:35:01.300 --> 00:35:04.780
And just learn to see it
as something that happened,

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:08.600
something you did, and
just kind of let it be.

00:35:08.600 --> 00:35:10.010
- Traces of your life.

00:35:10.010 --> 00:35:10.990
- Yeah.

00:35:10.990 --> 00:35:12.580
You know, we can't--

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:15.640
as much as we might want to
erase certain parts of our life

00:35:15.640 --> 00:35:19.840
that maybe weren't the best, we
can't do that, even if we try.

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:24.400
And yeah, if you have a
tattoo of whatever that

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:29.648
was, I think it can help you
just learn to move on from it,

00:35:29.648 --> 00:35:30.440
see it differently.

00:35:30.440 --> 00:35:31.870
- It comes from
memory, I suppose.

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:34.270
- Yeah.

